1. Summary


Bellabeat, a tech company with a focus on womens smart products plans to utilize smart device data to develop a market entry strategy. I will be analyzing Fitbit data in an attempt to identify trends that could assist them in achieving this objective.


2. Ask


Business Task: The business task is defined as searching for user patterns of usage of their smart devices in order to gain insights that would later better orientate marketing decisions


3. Prepare


3.1 Data Sources


For this study, Fitbit Fitness Tracker Data found on Kaggle.com will be used. The data was made avaliable through Mobius. Link is provided here: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/arashnic/fitbit


3.1 Accessibility & Privacy

The datset is open source, meaning the owner waived all rights to the ownership. This dataset can be freely used without any legal repercussions. The 33 users also agreed to having their data used in this process.


3.3 Metadata


This dataset generated by respondents to a distributed survey via Amazon Mechanical Turk between 03.12.2016-05.12.2016. Thirty eligible Fitbit users consented to the submission of personal tracker data, including minute-level output for physical activity, heart rate, and sleep monitoring. Individual reports can be parsed by export session ID (column A) or timestamp (column B). Variation between output represents use of different types of Fitbit trackers and individual tracking behaviors / preferences.


3.4 Data Structure


There are 18 different csvs provided. The data is quantitative, and certain subjects are presented with multiple different formats (wide vs.long). Of the 18 provided these are the ones I will use for this case study:


Table Name Type Description
dailyActivity_merged Microsoft Excel CSV Trackings Steps, Distance, Intensities, and Calories for 33 people over 31 days.
dailyCalories_merged Microsoft Excel CSV Daily Calories over 31 days of 33 users
dailyIntensities_merged Microsoft Excel CSV Daily Intensity over 31 days of 33 users
dailySteps_merged Microsoft Excel CSV Daily Steps for 33 users over 31 days
heartrate_seconds_merged Microsoft Excel CSV heartrate logs for just 7 users
hourlyCalories_merged Microsoft Excel CSV 33 users, 31 days, Hourly Calories
hourlyIntensities_merged Microsoft Excel CSV 33 users, 31 days, Average and Total intensities
hourlySteps_merged Microsoft Excel CSV 33 users, 31 days, Hourly Steps


3.5 Data credibility and limitations


With only 30 users, it is important to note the possibility of sampling bias. There are also different levels of use between participants, meaning those that contribute more data likely have more influence on the conclusions made. The duration of the study also poses an issue, with only 2 months of data. These will be taken into account throughout the case study.


4. Process


Both the size of the dataset and the need for visualization in this project led to the use Rstudio to complete the business task.

4.5 Changing Data Types


The dates for dailyActivity and sleepDay will be converted as.Date(), while hourlySteps & hourlyCals will be converted to datetime using as.POSIXct().


dailyActivity<-dailyActivity %>% 
  rename(date=activity_date) %>% 
  mutate(date=as.Date(date, format="%m/%d/%y"))

sleepDay<-sleepDay %>% 
  rename(date=sleep_day) %>% 
  mutate(date=as.Date(date, format="%m/%d/%y"))

hourlySteps<- hourlySteps %>% 
  rename(date_time=activity_hour) %>% 
  mutate(date_time = as.POSIXct(date_time,format ="%m/%d/%y %H:%M", tz="UTC"))

hourlyCals<- hourlyCals %>% 
  rename(date_time=activity_hour) %>% 
  mutate(date_time=as.POSIXct(date_time, format="%m/%d/%Y %I:%M:%S %p", tz=Sys.timezone()))

5.2 Quantifying Activity Levels


Depending on how many steps taken or calories burned, each participant is going to be put into a category.


For Steps:


Sedentary hour: <350 steps
Lightly active hour: 351-535
Fairly active hour: 536-714
Very active hour: 715<


These numbers were found by taking the classifications from https://www.10000steps.org.au/articles/counting-steps/. This source included how many steps were required to fit into these categories per day, but to find the requirements for each hour I took the daily levels and divided by 14hrs (average time awake per day).


step_hour_type <- hourly_average %>%
  mutate(hour_type = case_when(
    meanH_steps < 150 ~ "sedentary",
    meanH_steps >= 150 & meanH_steps < 400 ~ "lightly active", 
    meanH_steps >= 400 & meanH_steps < 649 ~ "fairly active", 
    meanH_steps >= 650 ~ "very active"
  )) %>% 
  drop_na()

head(step_hour_type)

For Calories:


While there might be less clear range here, I will do the same with calories per hour.


Sedentary hour: <59
Lightly active hour: 60-89
Fairly active hour: 90-119
Very active hour: 120<


I had to create this range for myself, following a similar path to hourly_steps by breaking the types into quartiles. Since the sedentary type required 50% less steps than the very active type, I made sure to do the same as well with the requirements for each calorie category.


 cal_hour_type <- hourly_average %>%
  mutate(hour_type = case_when(
    mean_Hcals < 85 ~ "sedentary",
    mean_Hcals >= 85 & mean_Hcals < 127.5 ~ "lightly active", 
    mean_Hcals >= 127.5 & mean_Hcals < 170 ~ "fairly active", 
    mean_Hcals >= 170~ "very active"
  )) %>% 
  drop_na()

The count of light activity is much more present in the calories burned graph. I believe this could be due to weight differences in the participants. Meaning someone who is 400 pounds will burn more calories from 100 steps than an individual who weighs 100 pounds.


cal_hour_type %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=hour_type, fill=hour_type))+geom_bar()+theme(legend.position="none")+ggtitle("Count of Hourly Calories")
step_hour_type %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=hour_type,fill=hour_type))+geom_bar()+theme(legend.position="none")+ggtitle("Count of Hourly Steps")


One of our goals should be to reduce the amount of sedentary hours for our users. Of course we should still expect to see sedentary hours as very common due to our need for rest and recovery. Yet by promoting more steps every hour with a reminder (for example) we will have healthier customers who also have higher levels of engagement with our product.


5.3 Counting the sum of each Activity Type by Hour


To find the most active hours of the day, we will count the amount of times each type appears in the given hour.


Starting with Steps:

These charts produce some interesting results,


You can see the sedentary hours are most common overnight, this is (of course) due to the lack of movement during sleep. As day arrives, the count of increased activity types rises as well.
When looking at the other 3 types, you can see there is an odd amount of activity during the hours of 2-3am. This could either be individuals that like to have a night out, or a watch malfunction. Either way, unless malfunctions are very common, I believe it is largely due to sampling bias.
The time with the most activity appears to be slightly different depending between the two types. Exercises involving less steps and seem to peak slightly later in the day (around 13-19:00). Its important to note here that calories is a better indicator when tracking exercise types that require less movement. Exercises that do require movement will be shown by both increased steps & calories, and these appear to peak between 9-15:00 according to the activity graphs.
Much of this data will help the company build a complete profile of each user. Building this profile not only helps us correctly market to these individuals, but also helps the customers fulfill their fitness goals. For example, by sending a notification at their usual time of exercise reminding them to workout, we could see increased consistency in their routine.

This graph is much less clear than the former. You can see a large majority of the data is closer to the origin, which displays the frequency of low activity compared to high activity hours.
One of the most confusing things about this graph is that many of datapoints with the highest hourly step count average have very low calories being burned. This gives further evidence that there is a watch malfunction (as one cannot move without burning more calories).

On the other hand, calories can be burned without steps being taken, so we will treat this data as legitimate.


5.5 Stationary vs.Mobile Exercise


So how can we distinguish between an individual going for a run and a watch malfunction? One way is to find those that are both Very Active (in terms of mean hourly steps) and Sedentary (in terms of mean hourly calories burned). These are individuals that are taking a high amount of steps without burning virtually any calories, which is impossible. These results are likely due to a watch malfunction and should be treated as such.
Secondly, if an individual is Very Active in both categories, Very Active or Faily Active for both, or Fairly Active in Both, it is likely that they are exercising in a way that requires movement.
a similar method is used for the next category: those burning calories but not taking many steps are likely engaging in stationary exercise (weightlifting, yoga, etc..). By grouping those who are either Sedentary, Lightly Active (in terms of steps taken), with the Very Active calories burned type we will find those who are exercising without much movement. With steps taken, I am not considering Light Activity to be mobile exercise. The range of Light Exercise is low enough that simply walking to and from different equipment in a gym might be included in it. This should of course be a case by case depending on an individuals weight, age, and health. But due to limitations of this data this cannot be done.
This also presents another shortcoming of this product that should be highlighted. By allowing a customer to categorize their own workout, it will take much responsibility off this data to correctly group each individual based off steps and calories burned.
While you most definitely can categorize individuals from data collected, it would never be more accurate than simply asking the customer to declare what type of exercise they partook in. Having these user-created labels included in future data sets would also allow our models to have higher levels of accuracy. Being able to identify what type of exercise an individual is doing is vital because being able to categorize our customers means our marketing can be more tailored to each user.


Quantifying Stationary Exercise, Mobile Exercise, and Watch Malfunction:


stationary <- hourly_average %>%

6. Conclusion


The goal with this case study was to discover trends in smart device usage that would be beneficial to both Bellabeats marketing strategy and their customers. While I came to certain conclusions with the data provided, the limitations of the dataset illustrates a need for a larger scale project. The discoveries I made with the data provided are listed below:


High levels of device malfunction with step counting:


A little over 6% of the hourly data collected came from watch malfunctions. This percentage is too significant to be ignored. By having a system to detect watch malfunctions we can clean the set accordingly. It also should be noted to our engineers that this should be something they test for. If our watch had less malfunctions, or just a built in detection system to remove the impossible results we might have both happier customers and analysts.


How to identify certain activity types & the importance of self-identification:


During the case study I grouped individuals into either stationary or mobile exercise based on the data provided. By grouping these individuals we can will improve the accuracy of our marketing strategies. For example, we would be able to more accurately predict if an individual would be more interested in running or gym equipment based off their exercise preference.
To take this a step further, we should be directly asking and keeping track of what type of exercises our customers are partaking in. This would not only be more accurate and display a more complete picture, but also take a lot of pressure off our analysts to provide accurate findings.


Daily exercise times and notifications:


By looking at the distribution of the available hourly data, we can find each users usual time of exercise. By tracking a users daily exercise routine, our watch could send notifications around the time of usual activity to increase consistency and engagement.


Increased engagement with reduction of sedentary hours:


As these devices are marketed as smart fitness devices, most users will likely be interested in self improvement and increased activity. By notifying individuals with the intent to help reduce the count of sedentary hours we would be helping them with this goal, and (again) increasing engagement with our product. An example of this would be reminding users to stand and move once an hour.


Note:


Privacy concerns: In future cases, these individuals would need to be prompted and made aware of how their data is being used. The transparency of our process would be essential in gaining the trust of our users. These processes would improve the customer experience, so we should give the customer every guarantee that their data is being used for their own benefit.
Data Limitations: Again, this data was collected by 33 users over 31 days. More research is required to make any concrete conclusions. This is a great start and should be the first step in a larger scale project.
